#1 Metastatic colon cancer to the liver, unresectable liver disease
Basic cancer education has been provided to the patient at the request of Dr. Benton service.  I have had the opportunity to review the operative report, surgical pathology, laboratory values, and notes in Documents Browser.  I have reviewed these findings with the patient and answered questions.  I have discussed this case in detail with Dr. Martinez, my collaborating physician, who has guided my plan.
We have discussed the characteristics of the cancer, including the type of malignancy, size, grade, lymph node status, and stage of the cancer.
Mr. Graves is an established patient of our colleagues in APO New York, Missouri, Ochsner Hospital Seabrook.  He will be following-up with them, and therefore, I will not have him return postoperatively.  Dr. Martinez will visit with Mr. Graves prior to hospital dismissal for formal treatment recommendations.  Certainly, if the need arises in the future, I would be more than happy to help facilitate care.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

