#1 Metastatic colon cancer to the liver, unresectable liver disease

[end section id="20113"]

[start section id="20101"]

Jackie Harper, M.D. (566-6836).

[end section id="20101"]

[start section id="20102"]

Supervised by:  Chris Martinez, M.D.
Metastatic colon cancer to the liver; liver unresectable.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

I was asked by Dr. Harper's service to visit with Mr. Graves for postoperative education purposes.  Briefly, Mr. Graves is a very pleasant 53-year-old male from Norway Missouri.  He is an established patient of our colleagues in the Methodist Memorial Hospital in APO New York.
1.  December 2009 - underwent screening colonoscopy which identified a sigmoid mass.  Biopsies confirmed adenocarcinoma.  CEA was 79.4.  PET/CT showed bilobar liver metastases.
2.  December 2009 to August 2010 - underwent FOLFOX plus Avastin x12 cycles.  Had significant peripheral neuropathy of the hands and feet with some functional impairment with difficulty buttoning buttons and tying shoes from oxaliplatin exposure.  Interval imaging showed disease response.
3.  August 2010 - evaluated with a repeat CT and MRI showing several lesions in the liver, some of which were smaller and some of which were larger.  Patient seen by Drs. Blair Solomon and Pemberton and the consensus was to undergo primary resection of the colon cancer and a staged liver resection.
4.  September 10, 2010 - underwent sigmoid resection by Dr. Harper.  Surgical pathology noted a grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming 4.1-cm x 3.2-cm x 0.7-cm mass in the sigmoid colon invading through the muscularis propria into the pericolonic fat with minimal treatment effect.  The surgical margins were negative, and 1 of 15 regional lymph nodes was positive for metastatic adenocarcinoma.  Biopsy of the left lobe of the liver was consistent with metastatic grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma.  Due to the extensive disease in the liver, Dr. Solomon was unable to proceed with planned hepatic resection and liver disease was left in place.
Mr. Graves is continuing to recover from surgery and was sitting up in bed during our consultation today.

[end section id="20103"]

